The online study linked to this analysis creates a context in which duration estimates can be retrieved. The main purpose of this experiment is to explore how visualization can improve, assist or otherwise influence time estimations.

1 Research questions

1.1 Main research questions

  1. What is the effect of simulating and visualizing data on people’s task duration estimates?
    • Do their point estimates change overall (from first to third estimation)? Which part of the potential increase can be attributed to the visualization (from second to third estimation)?
    • Do their uncertainty ranges increase or change overall (from first to third estimation)? Which part can be be attributed to the visualization (from second to third estimation)?
  2. Do quantile dotplots help indicating 95% prediction intervals?
    • What is the size of the prediction interval participants indicate after seeing a quantile dotplot?
    • What is the effect of the number of dots on the actual size of the prediction interval?
  3. What is the effect of any feedback and of specific forms (slider vs visualization) on people’s decision making?
    • What is the overall difference between the first and the final decision on waiting time?
    • What is the difference between the first and the final decision on waiting time depending on feedback groups?
    • What is the overall difference between the first and the final decision on the likelihood that people would miss their train?
    • What is the difference between the first and final decision on the likelihood depending on feedback groups?
    • Do people using the visualization take longer to come to a decision than people using the slider?

1.2 Additional questions and analysis

  1. How do our results compare to previous work in psychology: How does breaking a task down into subtasks and considering events slowing one down or making one faster affect people’s estimation?
    1. Do central tendencies become more or less optimistic?
    2. Do the intervals become wider?
  2. Do people who tend to be early prefer longer waiting time?

1.3 Dependent variables

The dependent variables we measure are:

  1. Task 1 estimates
    • E1a and I1a: first estimate expressed as a symmetric interval: duration in minutes + size of interval (1, ∞).
    • E1b and I1b: second estimate (after breaking down into subtasks and slow and fast events)
    • E1c and I1c: third estimate (after seeing the chart)
    • E1d_lower and E1d_upper: each substep’s estimates expressed as a lower and upper bounds
  2. Task 2 estimates
    • E2a: first estimate of a departure time, before seeing, exploring data (in minutes before the train leaves) [0, 960]
    • E2b: second estimate of a departure time, after seeing the chart or exploring the slider (in minutes before the train leaves) [0, 960]
  3. Interaction log
    • Time they interact with the chart or the slider (1, ∞)
    • Range of values explored with the slider or chart [0,highest value]
  4. Logs of simulated data used during the experiment
    • The log of the first 10,000 (out of 100,000) samples of generated task 1 completion times drawn to compute the quantile dotplot during the experiment.
    • The log of the first 10,000 (out of 100,000) samples of generated task 2 completion times drawn to compute the feedback for task 2 during the experiment.
    • The likelihood to miss one’s train for each minute shown on the respective feedback mode.

Covariates: lateness measured as a 7-point Likert scale item [-3, 3].

1.4 Outcomes

The effects we are computing and looking at to find answers to our research questions.

  1. Considering the question what is the effect of simulating and visualizing data on people’s task duration estimates, we analyze the following outcomes:
    1. We compute percent change differences on the estimates made by participants.
      • From the first to the third estimate: (E1c - E1a) / E1a if around 0, then they stay the same, values > 0 indicate higher estimates (more pessimistic), values < 0 lower estimates (more optimistic). [within outcome]
      • From the second to the third estimate: (E1c - E1b) / E1b if around 0, estimates remain the same, > 0 indicate higher estimates for the third estimation (increased pessimism attributable to the visualization), < 0 lower estimates than before (increased optimism attributable to the visualization).
    2. We compute percent change differences on the interval size given by participants.
      • From the first to the third estimate: (I1c - I1a) / I1a if around 0, then they stay the same, values > 0 indicate larger intervals (increased sense of uncertainty after breaking into subtasks and seeing the result visualized), values < 0 smaller intervals (reduced sense of uncertainty). [within outcome]
      • From the second to the third estimate: (I1c - I1b) / I1b if around 0, interval size remain the same, > 0 indicate larger intervals for the third estimation (increased sense of uncertainty attributable to the visualization), < 0 smaller ranges (reduced sense of uncertainty attributable to the visualization).
  2. Considering the question if quantile dotplots help indicating 95% prediction intervals:
    • PI: the overall actual size of the prediction interval after seeing any quantile dotplot
    • PI_20 and PI_50: same as above but by number of dots participants saw [between outcome]
    • The difference between PI_20 and PI_50.
  3. Considering the question what is the effect of type of representation (slider vs visualization) on people’s decision we analyze
    • E2b - E2a: the increase in waiting time after seeing some form of feedback
    • Same as 2.1 but with the number of dots as a factor
    • Lh_feedback - Lh_initial: the increase in the number of trains acceptable to miss after seeing some form of feedback.
    • Same as 3.3 but with the number of dots as a factor

Outcomes for the additional analyses

  1. To check in how far our results are consistent with previous literature on the planning fallacy we compute
    • (E1b - E1a) / E1a: the percent change increase in estimates after participants were asked to make estimates for sub-tasks and to reflect on the likelihood of events increasing or decreasing the required time.
    • (I1b - I1a) / I1a: the percent change increase in the size of the interval after participants were asked to make estimates for sub-tasks and reflect on the likelihood of events increasing or decreasing the required time.

We plan one type of robustness check: how to interpret the central tendency given by participants. Participants indicate a central tendency and a symmetric interval around it. However, these are durations which are strictly positive and more likely log-normal distributed. As a robustness check we therefore transform the central tendency indicated by participants into the expected value of a log-normal distribution described by the interval given by participants.

For the inferential analysis further down in this document, we compare the results for both options in each analysis step. An output is only produced if the 95% bootstrapped confidence interval of the difference between the two options does not include 0.

data2 = read.csv("data/data2.csv")

3 Inferential Analysis

3.1 Main research questions

3.1.1 RQ1: What is the effect of simulating and visualizing data on people’s task duration estimates?

We hypothesize the dotplot will help participants make a more informed decision as the duration of a task can be represented with a mixture distribution, which is hard to mentally process. However, our study design does not allow us to establish a ground truth for the accuracy of their estimation and thus, we will only look at the influence (induced variation in estimates) of the dotplot.

Moreover, past research reports that underestimations are more often reported than overestimation (for medium to long tasks), so we are expecting too low values (underestimates) which are then corrected for greater values (less optimistic estimates). Still, the other way around might occur as it remains unclear whether the direction of this prediction bias (over- or underestimation) is fixed for this specific task, and the fact that more studies report underestimations might be due to the field they come from (see Halkjelsvik and Jørgensen (2012)). In other words, even though underestimates are more likely, according to the literature, overestimates would not necessarily mean the participants’ estimates are not erroneous.

  1. Do their point estimates change overall (from first to third estimation)? If so, it would mean the debiasing methods and/or the dotplot induced a change of beliefs.

3.1.2 RQ2: Do quantile dotplots help indicating 95% prediction intervals?

There were two conditions for the dotplot which made the number of dots (either 20 or 50) vary.

  1. A 95% prediction interval was required throughout the whole study. As the dot plot allows participants to count the dots and thus mentally compute a more precise estimation based on that instruction, their ability to understand and process the information presented to them can be investigated. Indeed, what is the size of the prediction interval people indicate after seeing a quantile dotplot? We expect to find a value around 95% but it might depend on whether this percentage is calculated based on the whole distribution, or what they see on the dotplot.

If this percentage coverage is based on the whole distribution:

# the dataframe to hold the results answering RQ2
df_rq2 = data.frame(name = character(), condition = character(), estimate = numeric(), ci_lower = numeric(), ci_upper = numeric(), order = integer())

obs21 = meanCI.bootstrap(coverage3, conf.level = lvl_conf, seed = seed2)
df_rq2 <- df_rq2 %>% compile.df(obs21, "Final estimate", "all", 1)

cat("The mean actual size of prediction interval of the third estimate is", formatCI(obs21,unit="%"),"\n")
## The mean actual size of prediction interval of the third estimate is  71%, 95% CI [ 66%,  75%]
if (obs21$ci_lower <= 95 & obs21$ci_upper >= 95) {
  cat("The data analysis suggests this is close enough to a 95% CI, as was explicitly requested.\n")
} else {
  cat("The data analysis suggests participants did not provide an estimation following a 95% CI.\n")
}
## The data analysis suggests participants did not provide an estimation following a 95% CI.
obs21_verif = diffMeanCI.bootstrap(coverage3,data2$coverage3,conf.level = lvl_conf, seed = seed2)
if (!(obs21_verif$ci_lower <= 0 & obs21_verif$ci_upper >= 0)) {
  cat("NOTICE: Whether the participants provide the median or the mean influences the data analysis' results.\n")
  cat("Difference between the two measures:", formatCI(obs21_verif,unit="%"),"\n")
}

  1. What is the effect of the number of dots on the actual size of the prediction interval? The 50-dot plot carries more information as outliers have a greater chance to appear. Thereby, we want to know whether the number of dots influences the size of the prediction interval, or in other words, if more dots lead to prediction interval covering more instances.
obs22_20 = meanCI.bootstrap(coverage_dotplot[num_dots == 20],conf.level = lvl_conf, seed = seed2)

3.2 Additional questions

3.2.1 Debiasing methods

How do our results compare to previous work in psychology? How does breaking a task down into subtasks and considering events slowing one down or making one faster affect people’s estimation?

Estimating the duration of smaller components of a whole task produces greater values, which are not necessarily more accurate. This result has been observed by Connolly and Dean (1997) with a software development task, and by Forsyth and Burt (2008). Hayes-Roth (1980) also investigated this debiasing method but this time with a task involving similar errands. More precisely, the given sub-steps were enter store, find desired object, wait in line, pay for object and leave store. Based on these studies’ findings, we expect the participants to provide greater aggregated estimates when focusing on each sub-components than when predicting for the whole task. Nonetheless, the effect it might induce on the second estimation is uncertain for it depends on the participants’ ability and willingness to take the previous information into account.

The selection of the second debiasing method used for this experiment was mainly motivated by the information on the participants’ beliefs it would provide. Byram (1997) conducted an experiment in which surprises were manipulated but the results were inconclusive.

  1. How similar remain people’s responses? If the two first estimations of the whole task’s duration are quite similar in distribution, then it means the two debiasing methods had no effect. However, if there is a difference, we cannot precisely tell which factor caused it.

3.2.2 Personal preferences

At the end of the study, the participants were asked whether they believed they were rather early or late on a 7-point Likert scale. We wish to use this data to observe whether it could help predict their preferences. We test this using a Kendall Tau correlation coefficient and test it for both the initial waiting time and the final chosen one.

  cat("All participants who were self-reported as rather early were irrational.\n")
} else {
  obs51 = kendall.corCI.bootstrap(lateness_rating, waiting_time,conf.level = lvl_conf, seed = seed2)
  cat("The Kendall's tau correlation coefficient for the waiting time and lateness ratings is", formatCI(obs51),"\n")
  if (obs51$ci_lower <= 0 & obs51$ci_upper >= 0) {
    cat("The data analysis does not allow us to say the preferred waiting time and the lateness rating are correlated.\n")
  } else if (obs51$ci_lower <= 1 & obs51$ci_upper >= 1) {
    cat("The data analysis suggests the preferred waiting time and the lateness rating are correlated (same).\n")
  } else if (obs51$ci_lower <= -1 & obs51$ci_upper >= -1) {
    cat("The data analysis suggests the preferred waiting time and the lateness rating are correlated (reverse).\n")
  } else {
    cat("The data analysis does not allow to conclude anything.\n")
  }
}
